tl;dr
--

Parse your date-time strings using [`LocalDateTime#parse(CharSequence text)`](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/time/LocalDateTime.html#parse-java.lang.CharSequence-) and use `DateTimeFormatter.ofPattern(&quot;uuuu-MM-dd&#39;T&#39;HH:mm:ss.SSS&quot;, Locale.ENGLISH)` to format the obtained `LocalDateTime`.


Details
--
Irrespective of whether you have one/two/three digits in the *fraction-of-second* part of your date-time strings, they are compliant with [ISO 8601](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_8601) standards and therefore, you do not need a `DateTimeFormatter` to parse your date-time strings into a `LocalDateTime` by using [`LocalDateTime#parse(CharSequence text)`](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/time/LocalDateTime.html#parse-java.lang.CharSequence-).

However, to keep three digits always in the string resulting from formatting the `LocalDateTime`, you need to use `.SSS` with the formatter i.e. `DateTimeFormatter.ofPattern(&quot;uuuu-MM-dd&#39;T&#39;HH:mm:ss.SSS&quot;, Locale.ENGLISH)`.

**Demo**:

    import java.time.LocalDateTime;
    import java.time.format.DateTimeFormatter;
    import java.util.Locale;
    import java.util.stream.Stream;
    
    public class Main {
        public static void main(String[] args) {
            Stream.of(
                    &quot;2018-08-04T09:07:12.421&quot;,
                    &quot;2018-08-04T09:07:12.42&quot;,
                    &quot;2018-08-04T09:07:12.4&quot;
                )
                .map(LocalDateTime::parse)
                .map(dt -&gt; dt.format(DateTimeFormatter.ofPattern(&quot;uuuu-MM-dd&#39;T&#39;HH:mm:ss.SSS&quot;, Locale.ENGLISH)))
                .forEach(System.out::println);
        }
    }

**Output**:

    2018-08-04T09:07:12.421
    2018-08-04T09:07:12.420
    2018-08-04T09:07:12.400

Learn more about the modern Date-Time API from **[Trail: Date Time](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/datetime/index.html)**.

**Note**: In March 2014, `java.time` API supplanted the [error-prone legacy date-time API](https://www.oracle.com/technical-resources/articles/java/jf14-date-time.html). Since then, it has been strongly recommended to use this modern date-time API.

